Project: University of Amsterdam | ALgorithms EXposed (ALEX) | Design Workshop (https://www.notion.so/University-of-Amsterdam-ALgorithms-EXposed-ALEX-Design-Workshop-39202603a9c347c9b96eb0c078a474a7?pvs=21)
Project Description (Internal Use):
In February 2020, Simply Secure planned and facilitated a one-day design thinking workshop to support Algorithms.exposed (ALEX), a browser extension that gathers algorithmic behaviors to reconstruct the proprietary algorithms that intrude into our lives.

A more usable tool means that more people can participate in ALEX, which furthers ALEX's mission to expose algorithms.

Through our research, there is a greater understanding of people's relationship to - data motivations to donate data
- willingness to donate data
- doubts and questions they have about data donation

Outlined opportunities for ALEX to improve currently, and grow in the future
Its outputs will serve users, researchers and policymakers by mapping the extent of personalization practices, the evidence of algorithmic targeting, and the associated damages.
Related Blog: Popping the Filter Bubble: Design Practices for Data Donation (https://www.notion.so/Popping-the-Filter-Bubble-Design-Practices-for-Data-Donation-f7da43ceb9904154a2e8f5d0de4090b3?pvs=21)

Project: Internews UX Fund | RiseUp VPN LEAP (https://www.notion.so/Internews-UX-Fund-RiseUp-VPN-LEAP-9917cc36ddf1494d8a95cbcd81f80de2?pvs=21)
Project Description (Internal Use):
Riseup offers VPN service to anyone online, but focuses primarily on human rights activists, journalists, and social justice workers due to the tool’s location anonymization feature and lack of sign-in, payment, or IP address logging requirements. 

Riseup asked us to redesign their entire user experience on desktop and manual selection (a feature that allows users to choose the exit point of their VPN) to both mobile and desktop. 
  
The ultimate goal of the project was not only to design and test the usability of manual selection, but also to position the Riseup development team to be able to incorporate sustainable, user-centered design into its culture and improve the usability of RiseUp VPN.

Project Description (Internal Use):
ADOPTABLE (Adaptable Digital and Organizational Protections by Transforming and Building Long-term Ecosystems)/USABLE resources focus on supporting maintainers of OSS, developer contributors and OSS tool teams to better understand design practices and how that can help them create more user centered tools. 

Includes resources and the engagements planned around these resources that are most relevant to the OSS tool developer community.

Intended Impact: To improve how OSS tool developers communicate user needs and focus by offering resources and engagements with designers working on OSS tools.

Impacts : Sustainability of OSS tools, User centred open source software, designer to developer relations

Project Description (Internal Use):
Sonar is an open source framework to manage, annotate, and full-text search through data, including media files. It uses peer-to-peer technology to replicate and share collections, and can be used to develop decentralized applications. Some use cases the arso team has explored include searchable and replicable media archives, research databases, blogs, archiving and searching chat logs.
The arso team consists of a handful of developers working together as a loose collective. Their work centers around preserving and exploring information and media.
The arso team reached out to Simply Secure for guidance on developing and testing relevant UX patterns. We expected that this might include patterns for key exchange, schema handling, multiwriter conflict resolution, or access management. Our shared goals were to work with actual and potential users on the refinement of UX patterns for P2P search and discovery.

Project Description (Internal Use):
Yasmina: 
As a Senior Fellow in the Supporting Usability and Design in Security Program, Yasmina collaborated with OTF and Simply Secure to conduct a yearlong research study. The initiative introduced and trained designers and developers who build Internet Freedom tools to the human-centered design methodology. By using this methodology in their development processes, they will be able to design more effective, usable, and useful tools for Internet Freedom.

Gus:
Her fellowship project will work with particular projects to identify what their usability needs are and develop solutions specific to their stage of development. These might include design workshops, metrics analysis, expert review, or more user testing. She will also be conducting an overarching research project that might be useful to a number of tool developers, as well as to the broader community of security trainers, usable-security researchers, and digital literacy educators.

Maina:
Her fellowship consists of understanding user motivation and how it can better guide secure behavior, focusing specifically on e-mail. Her research will concentrate on these three questions: (i) To what extent does a lack of user motivation contribute to the low adoption and use of secure email?, (ii) How can we motivate users to adopt and use secure e-mail?, and (iii) How can motivation be integrated effectively into the design of secure e-mail? She will focus on the link between user motivation and adoption, and test the impact of motivational interventions. The output of her research will recommend how to increase the uptake of secure e-mail for the general population.

Project: OTF Usability Lab 1 | Mapeo UX Design (https://www.notion.so/OTF-Usability-Lab-1-Mapeo-UX-Design-97cd135d07aa46a0acf535ba44fbd305?pvs=21)
Project Description (Internal Use):
We helped make Mapeo available to a wider group of users around the world, providing them with an easy way to collect, manage and report data about human rights abuses without depending on internet access that may be blocked or monitored. The ability of local groups to collaborate to collect evidence of human rights abuses combining photos, maps and key data will strengthen advocacy efforts at a national and international level.

Mapeo is an open-source toolkit designed in partnership with Indigenous communities for collaborative documentation of human rights abuses, with photos linked to geographic information and cryptographic proofs. Mapeo is resilient during censorship, blackout, and with limited or no connectivity, as data can be shared offline between devices. The local-first database does not require any setup and is embedded in the mobile and desktop apps.

Project Description (Internal Use): RFE/RL’s mission is to promote democratic values and institutions and advance human rights by reporting the news in countries where a free press is banned by the government or not fully established. In 23 countries, RFE/RL journalists provide what many people cannot get locally: uncensored news, responsible discussion, and open debate. RFE’s app relies on infrastructure called Pangea, which has been a part of RFE’s online presence since 1999, with the first mobile apps launched in 2007. Recently, despite spending resources on advertising, RFE has seen usership of their mobile apps decline. This collaboration between Simply Secure and RFE/RL seeks to dig into this drop in usership.

Project: OTF Usability Lab 1 | Snikket 1.0 (https://www.notion.so/OTF-Usability-Lab-1-Snikket-1-0-5416dba3754c4f128d0830f3515a4418?pvs=21), OTF SUA Lab 2 | T-008 | Coaching Snikket 2023 (https://www.notion.so/OTF-SUA-Lab-2-T-008-Coaching-Snikket-2023-b9e815c394954e80ac9374ea6b95c0c2?pvs=21), OTF SUA Lab 2 | T-002 | Snikket 2.0 (https://www.notion.so/OTF-SUA-Lab-2-T-002-Snikket-2-0-b56ae8ca1c934ab49fbc06349e512dd3?pvs=21)
Project Description (Internal Use):
Three projects to improve Snikket's usability by balancing the ease of learning and efficiency of use.

Snikket is an XMPP-based messaging platform that aims to provide an open and secure alternative to proprietary messaging apps such as WhatsApp, Facebook Messenger, and Telegram. Unlike most other messaging apps, Snikket can be hosted on an individual server (including Raspberry Pis) for more control and security. While the XMPP ecosystem remains fragmented and highly technical, Snikket’s goal is to fill the gap with consistency and usability.

Through the OTF Usability Lab, our work with Snikket focused on improving the user experience  across platforms and balancing out the ease of learning versus the efficiency of use. In particular, we did a heuristic review of Snikket apps and web interfaces, conducted a user study, carried out several UX design explorations and provided design recommendations to address areas where there are barriers for adaptation and improving the onboarding experience. An upcoming blog post will explore in more detail some of the implementations of this work.

- Also
Design retainer to help with UX/UI aspects of Snikket XMPP messaging app on iOS and Android.

Project Description (Internal Use):
To better understand barriers to the adoption of Signal in East Asia. There are teams focused on design, support, communications and growth, and there has been collaboration with user researchers in the past, but there is not currently a sustained practice around user research that feeds into product and growth planning. Aligned with some planned travel to better understand the SE Asia market and plan for the next few years, there is an opportunity to align some user research activities to better contextualize use of Signal in Japan, Korea and Taiwan specifically, and E Asia more broadly, particularly as the work can inform more politically volatile locations such has Hong Kong. This project and collaboration provides an opportunity to pilot incorporating user research into the design and development practice, as well as learn and explore some key research questions that will inform product and growth decision making over the next few years.

The Research Goals are:
• Understand expectations around privacy and communication in Japan, Taiwan and Korea, and situate them within the E. Asia context
• Understand how expectations and cultural norms impact user behavior when needing to communicate and share personal information
